   =20
      Activism
   =20
 =20

If you are an activist hedge fund, I guess you have two motivations:
=09You are, essentially, a value investor: You buy companies that are cheap=
 because they are mismanaged, and then you try to fix the mismanagement (by=
 yelling at management, running proxy fights, etc.) so the stock goes up.=
=09You probably=C2=A0do=C2=A0like conflict, right? You probably think that =
you could do a better job of running the company than management does. You =
want to win proxy fights, get board seats, so that you can impose your will=
 on the company =E2=80=94=C2=A0and so that,   in your=C2=A0next=C2=A0activi=
st engagement, the company will be scared of you and more likely to do what=
 you want.

You want to make money, and you want to win proxy fights. But you can make =
money while losing proxy fights, and you can lose money while winning them.=
=C2=A0Which is more important? Would you rather have a good track record as=
 a value investor or as a winner of proxy fights? If you ask an activist he=
dge fund manager about her successes, is she more likely to mention:
=09the time she waged a proxy fight against a public company, and the compa=
ny=E2=80=99s management took the fight seriously and improved its operation=
s in order to win the fight, with the result that (1) she lost the proxy fi=
ght and (2) the stock went up, or=09the time she waged a proxy fight agains=
t a public company, and won, and got some board seats, but the company cont=
inued to languish with her in charge, and the stock went down?

I don=E2=80=99t know, I am just asking the question. Anyway:
On Wednesday at the annual meeting of Walt Disney Co., shareholders elected=
 all of management=E2=80=99s choices to the board, turning aside the nomina=
tion of [activist investor Nelson] Peltz, while also rejecting his ally, fo=
rmer Disney finance chief Jay Rasulo, and a slate from another dissident gr=
oup. Iger was reelected with 94% support, according to people familiar with=
 the matter, who asked not to be identified discussing results that haven=
=E2=80=99t been announced publicly, while Peltz garnered 31% of the votes. =
In other words, a rout.
But also:

Nelson Peltz may have suffered a bruising defeat in his proxy battle with D=
isney Wednesday, but the sting could be eased by a gain the activist has sc=
ored on the investment.
Peltz=E2=80=99s Trian Partners has made around $300 million in profit on it=
s 16-month investment, most of it on paper, according to people familiar wi=
th the matter.
The firm invested around $800 million in Disney in 2022, buying much of its=
 stake when shares were around $88 apiece. ...
After subtracting the $25 million Trian expected to spend waging the campai=
gn, the firm=E2=80=99s profit to date comes out to about $300 million.
That is a roughly 40% return on the investment over the period Trian has ow=
ned the shares, which is about equal to the S&P 500=E2=80=99s return over t=
he same period.

I suppose the way to spin this is that Peltz forced Disney to improve its o=
perations and get serious about succession planning, which made the stock m=
ore valuable, so he lost the proxy fight.

