   =20
      Trump Media
   =20
 =20

On the one hand, as we   have   discussed, the stock price of Trump Media &=
 Technology Group Corp. has nothing to do with the company=E2=80=99s fundam=
entals. Last year Trump Media lost $58 million on $4 million of revenue, bu=
t the stock has a market capitalization of more than $6 billion. It is hard=
 to work out a model of =E2=80=9Cthis expected cash flows to shareholders f=
rom this company=E2=80=99s business have a present value of $6 billion.=E2=
=80=9D
On the other hand, there=C2=A0are=C2=A0cash flows to shareholders. Just not=
 from the=C2=A0business. The cash flows are from stock lending. Here=E2=80=
=99s=C2=A0the New York Times:

The demand to short Trump Media, the parent company of the social media pla=
tform Truth Social, is so great that stock lenders can charge enormous fees=
, making it hard for short-sellers to turn a profit unless the shares fall =
significantly. Still, there is a lot of interest in taking the bet. =E2=80=
=A6
There are roughly 137 million shares in the company, and only around five m=
illion of those are available to short-sellers. =E2=80=A6
According to S3, 4.9 million of the roughly five million available shares a=
re already on loan. As with any loan, when share owners lend their stock to=
 a short-seller, they charge a fee, usually expressed as an annual interest=
 rate on the stock=E2=80=99s current value. Typically, the fee for borrowin=
g stock is a fraction of a percentage point. For Trump Media, it has risen =
to 550 percent, Mr. Dusaniwsky said.
Trump Media=E2=80=99s stock currently trades at around $50. That means that=
 shorting it for a month would cost more than $20 per share.

Which means that=C2=A0buying=C2=A0the stock today and=C2=A0lending=C2=A0it =
for three months would cost $50 and bring in $60, assuming that the borrow =
cost stays high. (Obviously a risky assumption!
  [1]
) Even if the stock goes to zero at the end of the three months, you come o=
ut ahead. Many people are probably buying Trump Media stock as a meme-stock=
 bet on Donald Trump, but some people are probably buying it as a direction=
al bet on=C2=A0stock lending markets.=C2=A0
That is: Trump Media=E2=80=99s stock might really be trading at a price tha=
t reflects the present value of its expected future cash flows. It=E2=80=99=
s just that those cash flows don=E2=80=99t come from the company=E2=80=99s =
business, but from people betting against that business. There is something=
 somehow appropriate about that! You make the money from the haters.
Well, you=E2=80=99re not really=C2=A0making the money from haters, or not e=
xclusively. Many of the people=C2=A0shorting=C2=A0Trump Media are not=C2=A0=
making a bet against Trump, or the company=E2=80=99s fundamentals; they are=
 doing an arbitrage:
One large broker said much of the short trading was not an outright bet aga=
inst Trump Media. =E2=80=A6 Instead, the current trade driving demand is de=
signed to capture the difference between DJT=E2=80=99s stock price and outs=
tanding =E2=80=9Cwarrants,=E2=80=9D which will give the owners the right to=
 new stock at a fixed price as long as regulators approve the new shares.
When it went public, the special purpose acquisition company that merged wi=
th Trump Media=C2=A0issued about 14 million warrants, each entitling the ho=
lder to buy stock at $11.50 per share. This is fairly standard in SPAC deal=
s, and the terms of the warrants provide that they become exercisable 30 da=
ys after the merger (that is, roughly April 25), as long as Trump Media has=
 filed a registration statement for the underlying shares. (It hasn=E2=80=
=99t done so yet, but =E2=80=9CTMTG has agreed to use its best efforts to m=
eet these conditions and to file and maintain a current and effective prosp=
ectus,=E2=80=9D and I assume eventually it will.)
Those warrants closed yesterday at $18.51, against a stock price of $48.81.=
 If they were exercisable now, you could buy a warrant for $18.51 and=C2=A0=
pay $11.50 to exercise it, for a total cost of $30.01. Then you=E2=80=99d g=
et a share of stock that you could sell for $48.81, an $18.80 instant profi=
t. But they=E2=80=99re not exercisable now. Now, you could buy a warrant fo=
r $18.51, borrow the stock for roughly $20 a month or call it $15 for three=
 weeks, and sell it for $48.81. If all goes well, in three weeks the warran=
ts will be exercisable, you=E2=80=99ll pay $11.50 to exercise, and you=E2=
=80=99ll deliver the stock to close out the borrow. Your cost is $18.51 (wa=
rrant) plus $15 (stock borrow) plus $11.50 (exercise price), or about $45.0=
1; you sold the stock for $48.81, so you make a few bucks. There=E2=80=99s =
a little juice in the trade, on these rough hypothetical numbers, but not m=
uch. The market for Trump Media warrants is pretty efficient: The warrants =
are cheaper than the common stock, because the common stock is so expensive=
 to borrow.
  [2]

One more point here. Let us assume that Trump Media has the following prope=
rties:
=09Its stock has a market value of $6 billion or so.=09Its business generat=
es, in round numbers, nothing.

What is the best way for=C2=A0Donald Trump, who owns about 58% of the compa=
ny, to turn his ownership into money? The obvious answers are:
=09Sell some stock.=09Post the stock as collateral to borrow money from ban=
ks.
  [3]



These methods have problems. A big one is that he can=E2=80=99t do either o=
f them=C2=A0now, because he has signed a lock-up agreement that prohibits h=
im from selling or pledging stock for six months after the merger. Also, th=
ough, if Trump sells stock, that might deflate Trump Media=E2=80=99s price:=
 If he=E2=80=99s getting out, why should retail investors get in? And proba=
bly a bank will not lend all that much money, without recourse, against a m=
eme stock.
One less obvious answer, suggested to me by a reader, is: Trump Media=C2=A0=
itself=C2=A0could sell stock, to raise money, and then lend that money to T=
rump. This would be =E2=80=A6=C2=A0highly, highly unorthodox? But I think i=
t is technically allowed: Unlike in a traditional initial public offering, =
Trump Media=C2=A0is not subject to the lock-up agreement, so it=C2=A0could=
=C2=A0sell more stock. Would that crash the stock? Eh, probably, but if you=
r view of Trump Media is that it is a meme bet on Trump himself, =E2=80=9Cw=
e are raising money to give to Trump for whatever purposes he wants=E2=80=
=9D might actually be a good pitch.
  [4]

Another less obvious answer, suggested to me by a different reader, is: Cou=
ld Trump=C2=A0lend out his stock to short sellers?=C2=A0Right now=C2=A0some=
=C2=A0Trump Media shareholders are making money by lending their stock to h=
aters; can Trump himself get in on that action? Probably not, is the answer=
. For one thing, the lock-up agreement says that he can=E2=80=99t =E2=80=9C=
lend, offer, pledge, hypothecate, encumber,=E2=80=9D etc. his stock. Even a=
fter the lock-up expires, though, as a 58% shareholder an officer, there wo=
uld probably be legal restrictions on his shares: He can=E2=80=99t sell the=
m freely, so he=E2=80=99d probably be restricted from lending them too. But=
 making money from people betting against him would be a pretty fitting way=
 for this to work.

 =20
   =20
      Paramount
   =20
 =20

I wrote yesterday that, if you want to do a merger with a public company, i=
t helps to already own most of the company, but it can also make things mor=
e complicated. The Wall Street Journal reports:

Members of Paramount Global=E2=80=99s board agreed to enter exclusive merge=
r discussions with Skydance, favoring it over a recent $26 billion all-cash=
 offer from private-equity firm Apollo Global Management.
The move means the entertainment conglomerate is putting on pause any conve=
rsations with other bidders for 30 days while it tries to work out a deal w=
ith Skydance, a production company led by David Ellison, people familiar wi=
th the matter said. =C2=A0
The decision could give Skydance an edge over Apollo, which earlier had off=
ered $11 billion for Paramount=E2=80=99s movie studio, but on Sunday offere=
d to buy the entire company for $26 billion, including debt. =E2=80=A6
Shari Redstone, Paramount Global=E2=80=99s controlling shareholder, has bee=
n in talks with Ellison to sell National Amusements, her family=E2=80=99s m=
edia empire that owns about 77% of the voting shares of Paramount, since la=
te last year. =C2=A0
The two have already agreed to terms, but Skydance has made it clear that t=
o close that deal, it needs to make sure that it is allowed to merge their =
studios, something it can=E2=80=99t do just by buying National Amusements. =
=E2=80=A6=C2=A0
Merging Paramount Global and Skydance requires a second deal that has to be=
 approved by an independent committee of directors at Paramount. That commi=
ttee must approve that the deal is good for all shareholders, not just Nati=
onal Amusements.

That is, roughly:
=09Apollo went to Paramount=E2=80=99s board and offered to buy all of the s=
tock for cash at a $26 billion enterprise value.=09Skydance went to Paramou=
nt=E2=80=99s controlling shareholder, Shari Redstone, and offered to buy ju=
st=C2=A0her=C2=A0stock =E2=80=94=C2=A0but only if Paramount=E2=80=99s board=
 also allowed it to merge its studio with Paramount.=09The board agreed to =
negotiate exclusively with Skydance.

We are missing some details here. How much did Skydance offer Redstone for =
her stock, for instance? What sort of merger terms did it propose to Paramo=
unt? (Shareholders =E2=80=9Cmight have indigestion at a Skydance deal that =
essentially leaves Paramount public, versus taking a cash premium from Apol=
lo,=E2=80=9D noted Rosenblatt Securities, and Bloomberg Intelligence notes =
that =E2=80=9CSkydance's desire to acquire control through parent company N=
ational Amusements suggests the deal will be complicated and may entail a t=
wo-step process.=E2=80=9D) And how feasible was Apollo=E2=80=99s offer? (=
=E2=80=9CParamount=E2=80=99s directors opted to move forward with Skydance =
as it wasn=E2=80=99t clear how Apollo would finance its bid,=E2=80=9D repor=
ts the Journal. I feel like =E2=80=9Cehh Apollo, those jokers, they can=E2=
=80=99t raise that kind of money=E2=80=9D is not a common response to an Ap=
ollo takeover proposal these days.
  [5]
)
Still, you can see the rough shape of the problem. Paramount has two classe=
s of stock outstanding, Class A and Class B. Class A has one vote per share=
; Class B has no votes. There are about 40.7 million shares of Class A outs=
tanding, and about 612 million shares of Class B. National Amusements owns =
about 9.7% of the total stock, but 77.4% of the Class A: It has complete vo=
ting control while owning less than 10% of the economics.
So if you want to=C2=A0acquire=C2=A0Paramount, the obvious two-step process=
 is:
=09Pay up for Shari Redstone=E2=80=99s 10% of the company, which is a contr=
olling stake, and=09Once you control the company, pay a lot less for the ot=
her 90%.

As I said yesterday, there are safeguards against that. The main one is tha=
t Paramount=E2=80=99s board has appointed a special committee of independen=
t directors to negotiate and approve any deal; the special committee has to=
 work on behalf of all shareholders, and will presumably reject a deal that=
 is really good for Redstone and bad for the rest of the shareholders.
But as I also said yesterday, these deals tend to be controversial and lead=
 to lawsuits. If Redstone has a deal to sell to Skydance, then in some sens=
e the board=C2=A0can=E2=80=99t=C2=A0negotiate a deal with Apollo: Paramount=
 can=E2=80=99t do any sort of merger without the approval of the 77.4% Reds=
tone stake, so if Redstone doesn=E2=80=99t want to sell to Apollo there is =
no deal to be done. All the board can do is negotiate the best possible dea=
l for shareholders=C2=A0that Redstone will agree to. And so it can end up n=
egotiating exclusively with Skydance even while there are other bidders out=
 there, because Skydance has a deal with the controlling shareholder.

 =20
   =20
      Comp is down
   =20
 =20

It used to be that the big investment banking was the generic way to become=
 rich. If you were a young person with fancy credentials, a strong desire f=
or money, and no strong preferences or interests, it was kind of natural to=
 go to a bank. =E2=80=9COddly enough,=E2=80=9D Michael Lewis wrote of his f=
irst day as a Salomon Brothers=C2=A0bond salesman with a Princeton art hist=
ory degree,=C2=A0=E2=80=9CI didn=E2=80=99t really imagine I was going to wo=
rk, more as if I were going to collect lottery winnings.=E2=80=9D
That was in 1985, and the next two decades or so were good, dynamic, lucrat=
ive times for the big investment banks. They dominated finance, and they in=
novated, building new products that increased their dominance and brought i=
n lots of money.
But now it is 2024 and things have changed. Corporate dealmaking is dominat=
ed by private equity firms, buyout financing is increasingly done by privat=
e credit, trading is increasingly done by hedge funds and proprietary tradi=
ng firms. Those are the places to make a lot of money in finance these days=
. More broadly, the generic way to get rich these days is in computer techn=
ology; the aimlessly well-educated now go to Meta or Alphabet, not Goldman =
Sachs.
Still, =E2=80=9CWall Street=E2=80=9D (meaning big investment banks) has ret=
ained its image as a generic wealth creator, which can lead to disappointme=
nt. At the New York Post, Lydia Moynihan reports that =E2=80=9Chundreds of =
thousands of junior bankers are cutting back after their bonuses were a bus=
t this year,=E2=80=9D with anecdotes like this:

One vice president at a large firm who has a one bedroom in the West Villag=
e, albeit a walkup, said after receiving even less this year than he did la=
st year, he has tried to scale back the number of times he eats out to two =
nights a week instead of three or four.
At his favorite spots =E2=80=94 Carbone where branzino costs $95, Dante=E2=
=80=99s where veal Milanese is $60 and Saint Theo=E2=80=99s where lamb chop=
s are $68 =E2=80=94 a dinner tab can quickly balloon to $300 or more and a =
drinks tab can easily hit $100 for a date. =E2=80=A6
=E2=80=9CFirst year employees are only making a $100,000 salary in New York=
 City. They rely on a decent bonus to pay their rent,=E2=80=9D a source in =
his 60s, who has been working as a banker for four decades, said.
The source, who noted the median Manhattan rent is $4,257 according to a St=
reetEasy study from February said he =E2=80=9Cfelt for the kids.=E2=80=9D

What is the world coming to when the investment banking kids can=E2=80=99t =
even afford the branzino at Carbone.

 =20
   =20
      Meanwhile at Meta
   =20
 =20

Here is a Bloomberg Businessweek story about a guy at Meta Platforms Inc. w=
ho used its internal chat system to solicit=C2=A0his co-workers to invest i=
n his real estate venture. A bunch of them invested and then=C2=A0the ventu=
re failed, =E2=80=9Cleaving about 160 people who=E2=80=99d found real estat=
e investments via the platform, including the dozens of Meta employees, wit=
h an estimated $50 million in losses.=E2=80=9D Meta has the deepest pockets=
 nearby, so of course the employees are half-heartedly blaming the company:
Meta had no direct connection to the episode, but that doesn=E2=80=99t nece=
ssarily matter when people feel burned. Employees complained to the company=
 that it should take responsibility for what happens on its internal chatro=
oms. =E2=80=9CMaybe [Meta] should have had a policy against any sort of pro=
motions like that,=E2=80=9D says Jeff Smith, a former Facebook product desi=
gner who says he lost more than $50,000. =E2=80=9CI think something like th=
is could happen at any workplace.=E2=80=9D
Any=C2=A0workplace? How many workplaces do you think there are where dozens=
 of people casually invest five-figure sums in their co-worker=E2=80=99s sp=
eculative real estate platform after reading about it on the company Slack?=
 This does not seem like a big problem for, say, Goldman Sachs vice preside=
nts. Really this episode is a good bit of recruiting for Meta: =E2=80=9CCom=
e to Meta and you can afford to be as casual with your money as we were.=E2=
=80=9D

