<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">On the one hand, as we <a href=3D"https://link=
.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/34928529.256352/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZ=
XJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjQtMDQtMDEvdHJ1bXAtbWVkaWEtcy1idXNpbmVz=
cy1kb2Vzbi10LW1hdHRlcj9jbXBpZD1CQkQwNDA0MjRfTU9ORVlTVFVGRiZ1dG1fbWVkaXVtPWV=
tYWlsJnV0bV9zb3VyY2U9bmV3c2xldHRlciZ1dG1fdGVybT0yNDA0MDQmdXRtX2NhbXBhaWduPW=
1vbmV5c3R1ZmY/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB52977aa3" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" ite=
mscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decora=
tion: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #0000=
00; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">  have</a> <a href=
=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/34928529.256352/aHR0cHM6L=
y93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjQtMDQtMDMvdHJ1bXAtbWVk=
aWEtcy1mb3VuZGVycy1hcmUtZmlnaHRpbmc_Y21waWQ9QkJEMDQwNDI0X01PTkVZU1RVRkYmdXR=
tX21lZGl1bT1lbWFpbCZ1dG1fc291cmNlPW5ld3NsZXR0ZXImdXRtX3Rlcm09MjQwNDA0JnV0bV=
9jYW1wYWlnbj1tb25leXN0dWZm/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB582d7d80" itemprop=3D"S=
toryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000=
; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom=
-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">  dis=
cussed</a>, the stock price of Trump Media &amp; Technology Group Corp. has=
 nothing to do with the company=E2=80=99s fundamentals. Last year Trump Med=
ia lost $58 million on $4 million of revenue, but the stock has a market ca=
pitalization of more than $6 billion. It is hard to work out a model of =E2=
=80=9Cthis expected cash flows to shareholders from this company=E2=80=99s =
business have a present value of $6 billion.=E2=80=9D</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">On the other hand, there=C2=A0<em>are=C2=A0</e=
m>cash flows to shareholders. Just not from the=C2=A0<em>business</em>. The=
 cash flows are from stock lending. Here=E2=80=99s=C2=A0<a href=3D"https://=
link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/34928529.256352/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cubnl0a=
W1lcy5jb20vMjAyNC8wNC8wMy9idXNpbmVzcy90cnVtcC1tZWRpYS1zaG9ydC1zZWxsaW5nLmh0=
bWw/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB075b06f3" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"=
itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none=
 !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border=
-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">the New York Times</a>:</p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The demand to short Trump Media, the parent co=
mpany of the social media platform Truth Social, is so great that stock len=
ders can charge enormous fees, making it hard for short-sellers to turn a p=
rofit unless the shares fall significantly. Still, there is a lot of intere=
st in taking the bet. =E2=80=A6</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">There are roughly 137 million shares in the co=
mpany, and only around five million of those are available to short-sellers=
. =E2=80=A6</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">According to S3, 4.9 million of the roughly fi=
ve million available shares are already on loan. As with any loan, when sha=
re owners lend their stock to a short-seller, they charge a fee, usually ex=
pressed as an annual interest rate on the stock=E2=80=99s current value. Ty=
pically, the fee for borrowing stock is a fraction of a percentage point. F=
or Trump Media, it has risen to 550 percent, Mr. Dusaniwsky said.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Trump Media=E2=80=99s stock currently trades a=
t around $50. That means that shorting it for a month would cost more than =
$20 per share.</p>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Which means that=C2=A0<em>buying=C2=A0</em>the=
 stock today and=C2=A0<em>lending=C2=A0</em>it for three months would cost =
$50 and bring in $60, assuming that the borrow cost stays high. (Obviously =
a risky assumption!<a class=3D"footnote-index" href=3D"#footnote-1" style=
=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: =
1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: none !important; ba=
ckground-color: transparent !important; display: inline-block;">
<span>[1]</span>
</a>) Even if the stock goes to zero at the end of the three months, you co=
me out ahead. Many people are probably buying Trump Media stock as a meme-s=
tock bet on Donald Trump, but some people are probably buying it as a direc=
tional bet on=C2=A0<em>stock lending markets</em>.=C2=A0</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">That is: Trump Media=E2=80=99s stock might rea=
lly be trading at a price that reflects the present value of its expected f=
uture cash flows. It=E2=80=99s just that those cash flows don=E2=80=99t com=
e from the company=E2=80=99s business, but from people betting against that=
 business. There is something somehow appropriate about that! You make the =
money from the haters.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Well, you=E2=80=99re not <em>really=C2=A0</em>=
making the money from haters, or not exclusively. Many of the people=C2=A0<=
em>shorting=C2=A0</em>Trump Media are <em>not=C2=A0</em>making a bet agains=
t Trump, or the company=E2=80=99s fundamentals; they are doing an arbitrage=
:</p>
<blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">One large broker said much of the =
short trading was not an outright bet against Trump Media. =E2=80=A6 Instea=
d, the current trade driving demand is designed to capture the difference b=
etween DJT=E2=80=99s stock price and outstanding =E2=80=9Cwarrants,=E2=80=
=9D which will give the owners the right to new stock at a fixed price as l=
ong as regulators approve the new shares.</p></blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">When it went public, the special purpose acqui=
sition company that merged with Trump Media=C2=A0issued about <a href=3D"ht=
tps://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/34928529.256352/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3c=
uc2VjLmdvdi9BcmNoaXZlcy9lZGdhci9kYXRhLzE4NDk2MzUvMDAwMTEwNDY1OTIxMTEzNTQxL3=
RtMjEyNzAzNWQxXzQyNGI0Lmh0bQ/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB7230350a" itemprop=3D=
"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #0000=
00; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bott=
om-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">14 =
million warrants</a>, each entitling the holder to buy stock at $11.50 per =
share. This is fairly standard in SPAC deals, and the terms of the warrants=
 provide that they become exercisable 30 days after <a href=3D"https://link=
.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/34928529.256352/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuc2VjLmdvd=
i9peD9kb2M9L0FyY2hpdmVzL2VkZ2FyL2RhdGEvMTg0OTYzNS8wMDAxMTQwMzYxMjQwMTY3MTkv=
ZWYyMDAyNTM0Ml84ay5odG0/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB9b9ec2a2" itemprop=3D"Stor=
yLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; t=
ext-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-co=
lor: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">the merg=
er</a> (that is, roughly April 25), as long as Trump Media has filed a regi=
stration statement for the underlying shares. (It hasn=E2=80=99t done so ye=
t, <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/34928529.256352=
/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuc2VjLmdvdi9peD9kb2M9L0FyY2hpdmVzL2VkZ2FyL2RhdGEvMTg0OTYzNS=
8wMDAxMTQwMzYxMjQwMTcwMTEvZWYyMDAyNTM1NV8xMGsuaHRt/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23c=
C186c6c4b" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank"=
 style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-w=
idth: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; backgr=
ound-color: #ccc;">but</a> =E2=80=9CTMTG has agreed to use its best efforts=
 to meet these conditions and to file and maintain a current and effective =
prospectus,=E2=80=9D and I assume eventually it will.)</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Those warrants closed yesterday at $18.51, aga=
inst a stock price of $48.81. If they were exercisable now, you could buy a=
 warrant for $18.51 and=C2=A0pay $11.50 to exercise it, for a total cost of=
 $30.01. Then you=E2=80=99d get a share of stock that you could sell for $4=
8.81, an $18.80 instant profit. But they=E2=80=99re not exercisable now. No=
w, you could buy a warrant for $18.51, borrow the stock for roughly $20 a m=
onth or call it $15 for three weeks, and sell it for $48.81. If all goes we=
ll, in three weeks the warrants will be exercisable, you=E2=80=99ll pay $11=
.50 to exercise, and you=E2=80=99ll deliver the stock to close out the borr=
ow. Your cost is $18.51 (warrant) plus $15 (stock borrow) plus $11.50 (exer=
cise price), or about $45.01; you sold the stock for $48.81, so you make a =
few bucks. There=E2=80=99s a little juice in the trade, on these rough hypo=
thetical numbers, but not much. The market for Trump Media warrants is pret=
ty efficient: The warrants are cheaper than the common stock, because the c=
ommon stock is so expensive to borrow.<a class=3D"footnote-index" href=3D"#=
footnote-2" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; bord=
er-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: no=
ne !important; background-color: transparent !important; display: inline-bl=
ock;">
<span>[2]</span>
</a></p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">One more point here. Let us assume that Trump =
Media has the following properties:</p>
<ul style=3D"list-style-type: disc; padding-left: 40px; margin: 16px 0;">=
=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">Its stock has a market value of $6 bil=
lion or so.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">Its business generates=
, in round numbers, nothing.</li>
</ul>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">What is the best way for=C2=A0<em>Donald Trump=
</em>, who owns about 58% of the company, to turn his ownership into money?=
 The obvious answers are:</p>
<ol style=3D"list-style-type: decimal; padding-left: 40px; margin: 16px 0;"=
>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">Sell some stock.</li>=09<li style=3D"=
margin-bottom: 5px;">Post the stock as collateral to borrow money from bank=
s.<a class=3D"footnote-index" href=3D"#footnote-3" style=3D"color: #000000;=
 text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-=
color: #000000; border-bottom-style: none !important; background-color: tra=
nsparent !important; display: inline-block;">
<span>[3]</span>
</a>
</li>
</ol>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">These methods have problems. A big one is that=
 he can=E2=80=99t do either of them=C2=A0<em>now</em>, because he has signe=
d <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/34928529.256352/=
aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuc2VjLmdvdi9peD9kb2M9L0FyY2hpdmVzL2VkZ2FyL2RhdGEvMTg0OTYzNS8=
wMDAxMTQwMzYxMjQwMTY3MTkvZWYyMDAyNTM0Ml84ay5odG0/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cD9=
b9ec2a2" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" s=
tyle=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-wid=
th: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; backgrou=
nd-color: #ccc;">a lock-up agreement</a> that prohibits him from selling or=
 pledging stock for six months after the merger. Also, though, if Trump sel=
ls stock, that might deflate Trump Media=E2=80=99s price: If he=E2=80=99s g=
etting out, why should retail investors get in? And probably a bank will no=
t lend all that much money, without recourse, against a meme stock.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">One less obvious answer, suggested to me by a =
reader, is: Trump Media=C2=A0<em>itself=C2=A0</em>could sell stock, to rais=
e money, and then lend that money to Trump. This would be =E2=80=A6=C2=A0hi=
ghly, highly unorthodox? But I think it is technically allowed: Unlike in a=
 traditional initial public offering, Trump Media=C2=A0is not subject to th=
e lock-up agreement, so it=C2=A0could=C2=A0sell more stock. Would that cras=
h the stock? Eh, probably, but if your view of Trump Media is that it is a =
meme bet on Trump himself, =E2=80=9Cwe are raising money to give to Trump f=
or whatever purposes he wants=E2=80=9D might actually be a good pitch.<a cl=
ass=3D"footnote-index" href=3D"#footnote-4" style=3D"color: #000000; text-d=
ecoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: =
#000000; border-bottom-style: none !important; background-color: transparen=
t !important; display: inline-block;">
<span>[4]</span>
</a></p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Another less obvious answer, suggested to me b=
y a different reader, is: Could Trump=C2=A0<em>lend out his stock to short =
sellers?=C2=A0</em>Right now=C2=A0<em>some=C2=A0</em>Trump Media shareholde=
rs are making money by lending their stock to haters; can Trump himself get=
 in on that action? Probably not, is the answer. For one thing, <a href=3D"=
https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/34928529.256352/aHR0cHM6Ly93d=
3cuc2VjLmdvdi9peD9kb2M9L0FyY2hpdmVzL2VkZ2FyL2RhdGEvMTg0OTYzNS8wMDAxMTQwMzYx=
MjQwMTY3MTkvZWYyMDAyNTM0Ml84ay5odG0/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cE9b9ec2a2" item=
prop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color=
: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; bord=
er-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #cc=
c;">the lock-up agreement</a> says that he can=E2=80=99t =E2=80=9Clend, off=
er, pledge, hypothecate, encumber,=E2=80=9D etc. his stock. Even after the =
lock-up expires, though, as a 58% shareholder an officer, there would proba=
bly be legal restrictions on his shares: He can=E2=80=99t sell them freely,=
 so he=E2=80=99d probably be restricted from lending them too. But making m=
oney from people betting against him would be a pretty fitting way for this=
 to work.</p>
