t=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; bor=
der-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: s=
olid; background-color: #ccc;">reports</a>:</p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Members of Paramount Global=E2=80=99s board ag=
reed to enter exclusive merger discussions with Skydance, favoring it over =
a recent $26 billion all-cash offer from private-equity firm Apollo Global =
Management.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The move means the entertainment conglomerate =
is putting on pause any conversations with other bidders for 30 days while =
it tries to work out a deal with Skydance, a production company led by Davi=
d Ellison, people familiar with the matter said. =C2=A0</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The decision could give Skydance an edge over =
Apollo, which earlier had offered $11 billion for Paramount=E2=80=99s movie=
 studio, but on Sunday offered to buy the entire company for $26 billion, i=
ncluding debt. =E2=80=A6</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Shari Redstone, Paramount Global=E2=80=99s con=
trolling shareholder, has been in talks with Ellison to sell National Amuse=
ments, her family=E2=80=99s media empire that owns about 77% of the voting =
shares of Paramount, since late last year. =C2=A0</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The two have already agreed to terms, but Skyd=
ance has made it clear that to close that deal, it needs to make sure that =
it is allowed to merge their studios, something it can=E2=80=99t do just by=
 buying National Amusements. =E2=80=A6=C2=A0</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Merging Paramount Global and Skydance requires=
 a second deal that has to be approved by an independent committee of direc=
tors at Paramount. That committee must approve that the deal is good for al=
l shareholders, not just National Amusements.</p>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">That is, roughly:</p>
<ul style=3D"list-style-type: disc; padding-left: 40px; margin: 16px 0;">=
=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">Apollo went to Paramount=E2=80=99s boa=
rd and offered to buy all of the stock for cash at a $26 billion enterprise=
 value.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">Skydance went to Paramount=
=E2=80=99s controlling shareholder, Shari Redstone, and offered to buy <em>=
just=C2=A0her=C2=A0</em>stock =E2=80=94=C2=A0but only if Paramount=E2=80=99=
s board also allowed it to merge its studio with Paramount.</li>=09<li styl=
e=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">The board agreed to negotiate exclusively with Sk=
ydance.</li>
</ul>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">We are missing some details here. How much did=
 Skydance offer Redstone for her stock, for instance? What sort of merger t=
erms did it propose to Paramount? (Shareholders =E2=80=9Cmight have indiges=
tion at a Skydance deal that essentially leaves Paramount public, versus ta=
king a cash premium from Apollo,=E2=80=9D <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloo=
mbergbusiness.com/click/34928529.256352/aHR0cHM6Ly9ibGlua3MuYmxvb21iZXJnLmN=
vbS9uZXdzL3N0b3JpZXMvU0JGNlk3RFdYMlBTP2NtcGlkPUJCRDA0MDQyNF9NT05FWVNUVUZGJn=
V0bV9tZWRpdW09ZW1haWwmdXRtX3NvdXJjZT1uZXdzbGV0dGVyJnV0bV90ZXJtPTI0MDQwNCZ1d=
G1fY2FtcGFpZ249bW9uZXlzdHVmZg/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB34405a80" itemprop=
=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #0=
00000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-b=
ottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">=
noted Rosenblatt Securities</a>, and Bloomberg Intelligence notes that =E2=
=80=9CSkydance's desire to acquire control through parent company National =
Amusements suggests the deal will be complicated and may entail a two-step =
process.=E2=80=9D) And how feasible was Apollo=E2=80=99s offer? (=E2=80=9CP=
aramount=E2=80=99s directors opted to move forward with Skydance as it wasn=
=E2=80=99t clear how Apollo would finance its bid,=E2=80=9D reports the Jou=
rnal. I feel like =E2=80=9Cehh Apollo, those jokers, they can=E2=80=99t rai=
se that kind of money=E2=80=9D is not a common response to an Apollo takeov=
er proposal these days.<a class=3D"footnote-index" href=3D"#footnote-5" sty=
le=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width=
: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: none !important; =
background-color: transparent !important; display: inline-block;">
<span>[5]</span>
</a>)</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Still, you can see the rough shape of the prob=
lem. Paramount has <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click=
/34928529.256352/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuc2VjLmdvdi9peD9kb2M9L0FyY2hpdmVzL2VkZ2FyL2=
RhdGEvODEzODI4LzAwMDA4MTM4MjgyNDAwMDAwNy9wYXJhLTIwMjMxMjMxLmh0bQ/607f07ceef=
4b8524a319a23cFc49c2eed" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" tar=
get=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; b=
order-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style:=
 solid; background-color: #ccc;">two classes of stock outstanding</a>, Clas=
s A and Class B. Class A has one vote per share; Class B has no votes. Ther=
e are about 40.7 million shares of Class A outstanding, and about 612 milli=
on shares of Class B. National Amusements owns about 9.7% of the total stoc=
k, but 77.4% of the Class A: It has complete voting control while owning le=
ss than 10% of the economics.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">So if you want to=C2=A0<em>acquire=C2=A0</em>P=
aramount, the obvious two-step process is:</p>
<ol style=3D"list-style-type: decimal; padding-left: 40px; margin: 16px 0;"=
>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">Pay up for Shari Redstone=E2=80=99s 1=
0% of the company, which is a controlling stake, and</li>=09<li style=3D"ma=
rgin-bottom: 5px;">Once you control the company, pay a lot less for the oth=
er 90%.</li>
</ol>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">As I said yesterday, there are safeguards agai=
nst that. The main one is that Paramount=E2=80=99s board has appointed a sp=
ecial committee of independent directors to negotiate and approve any deal;=
 the special committee has to work on behalf of all shareholders, and will =
presumably reject a deal that is really good for Redstone and bad for the r=
est of the shareholders.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">But as I also said yesterday, these deals tend=
 to be controversial and lead to lawsuits. If Redstone has a deal to sell t=
o Skydance, then in some sense the board=C2=A0<em>can=E2=80=99t=C2=A0</em>n=
egotiate a deal with Apollo: Paramount can=E2=80=99t do any sort of merger =
without the approval of the 77.4% Redstone stake, so if Redstone doesn=E2=
=80=99t want to sell to Apollo there is no deal to be done. All the board c=
an do is negotiate the best possible deal for shareholders=C2=A0<em>that Re=
dstone will agree to</em>. And so it can end up negotiating exclusively wit=
h Skydance even while there are other bidders out there, because Skydance h=
as a deal with the controlling shareholder.</p>
